{"title_page": "Seo Linn", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Seo Linn\n| image            =\n| image_size       = 250\n| caption          = Seo Linn in 2019\n| background       = group_or_band\n| years_active     = 2013\u2013current\n| website          = {{url|seolinn.com/}}\n| origin           = Ireland\n| genre            = [[Irish Music]], [[Folk music|Folk Music]], [[Pop Music]], [[Celtic Music|Celtic]]\n| current_members  = [[Stiof\u00e1n \u00d3 Fearail]]<br/>Daith\u00ed \u00d3 Ruaidh<br/>Keith \u00d3 Briain<br/>Kev Shortall\n}}\n\n'''Seo Linn''' ({{IPA-ga|\u0283\u0254 l\u02b2\u026an\u0320\u02b2|}}, \"off we go\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ancroiait.wordpress.com/2013/09/18/123-learn-irish-some-nights/|title=123. Learn Irish \u2013 Some Nights|date=September 18, 2013}}</ref>) is an Irish folk/pop/rock group formed in Ireland that has been making music and performing since 2013.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/life-and-style/people/a-cure-has-been-found-for-irish-language-phobia-1.2556915|title=A cure has been found for Irish-language phobia|last=Valentine|first=Aoife|website=The Irish Times|language=en|access-date=2019-06-07}}</ref> The group consists of [[Stiof\u00e1n \u00d3 Fearail]] on vocals and guitar, Daith\u00ed \u00d3 Ruaidh on vocals, keyboard, and saxophone, Keith \u00d3 Briain on vocals, bass guitar, mandolin, and percussion, and Kevin Shortall on vocals, accordion, and percussion. They perform in both [[Irish language|Irish]] and [[English language|English]].\n\nTheir debut album, 'Solas', was released in 2017 featuring songs such as 'Ar Sc\u00e1th A Ch\u00e9ile', 'Music Makers' and their powerful rendition of the traditional Irish song, [[\u00d3r\u00f3 s\u00e9 do bheatha abhaile|\u00d3r\u00f3 'S\u00e9 Do Bheatha Abhaile]] entitled '\u00d3r\u00f3' on the album. The album won at the N\u00f3s Music Awards for '2017 Album of the Year'. The album consisted of a collection of songs that they had been writing since 2013 for vaious projects along with newly written material specifically for the album itself. Solas is the Irish word for 'light' and the image of a lightblub appears on the front of their CD symbolising a new idea and approach towards normalising the Irish language within contemporary folk-pop music.\n\nSeo Linn's second collection of original material, an EP entitled 'Marcus in the Wood/Marcas sa gCoill', was released in July 2019 containing singles 'Buy Me Time/Bain an Glas' and 'Darkeness Shines a Light/Soilsi\u00fa an Lae'.\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Early Years (2013 - 2017) ===\n\nThe band rose to prominence after meeting in [[Col\u00e1iste Lurgan]] in the Conamara Gaeltacht of West Galway where they worked for years establishing the TG Lurgan YouTube channel. Since the release of their 2013 cover video of [[Avicii]]'s 'Wake Me Up' both the TG Lurgan channel and the newly formed Seo Linn started to make waves.\n\nBy 2016, they had played [[Croke Park]], [[3Arena|The 3Arena]], [[Aviva Stadium]], [[Bord G\u00e1is Energy Theatre|The Board G\u00e1is Energy Theatre]], and a headline show in [[Vicar Street]].<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://seolinn.com/about/|title=About|website=Seo Linn|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-05-21}}</ref> They also managed to amass 32 million views on YouTube videos in this period and international headliner gigs in [[New York City|New York]], [[Melbourne]], [[Boston]], [[London]], [[Paris]], [[Edinburgh]] and even [[Uganda]].<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n=== Debut Album ''Solas'' (2017) ===\n\nSeo Linn wrote their first ever song, 'Ar Sc\u00e1th a Ch\u00e9ile' in Uganda in 2013 while the band were there with Irish charity [[Self Help Africa]]. The song is an uplifting song that speaks of the value behind the idea the 'unity is strength'. The song contains a lyric in [[Lugandan]], the Bantu language of the Baganda people of Uganda, that says 'kwegata bwe bugumu' which literally translates to 'togetherness is strength'. This phrase mirrors the Irish language phrase from which the song was titled, 'ar sc\u00e1th a ch\u00e9ile a mhaireann na daoine' meaning 'together people prosper'.\n\nIn 2016, as part of [[RT\u00c9]]'s widely acclaimed production entitled [[RT\u00c9 Centenary]], Seo Linn were chosen to write and record the song for the finale. They were asked to produce a contemporary, energetic, bilingual song inspired by lyrics from [[Arthur O'Shaughnessy]]'s 'Ode'. The line 'we are the music makers, we are the dreamer of dreams' was used in the chorus.\n\nSeo Linn's track \"[[The Irish Roar]]\" was chosen as the official [[Football Association of Ireland]] song for [[Euro 2016]]. Recorded in [[\u00c1ras Chr\u00f3n\u00e1in]] in [[Clondalkin]], the track tells the story of Irish successes in previous competitions and pays homage to travelling Irish fans.\n\nIn 'Sonas Studios' in [[Killarney]], [[Co. Kerry]], Seo Linn along with their producer, James Darkin, locked themselves in the studio for a whole night in order to create a modern take on the Irish traditional classic '\u00d3r\u00f3 'S\u00e9 Do Bheatha Abhaile' which resulted in their final track on the album '\u00d3r\u00f3'. Seo Linn's \u00d3r\u00f3 instantly became a fan favourite has amassed over 2 million views on YouTube alone.\n\n\"Accompanying the album is an interactive workbook for irish language learners with lyrics and chords, plus text written by the band on topics as diverse as sport, recipes, and even mallachta\u00ed, or insults, all as Gaeilge.\"<ref name=\"Beating\"/>  \"It encapsulates the band\u2019s ethos: \u201cEssentially what we\u2019re trying to do with the book is to take [Gaeilge] out of the classroom setting and make it real for young people.\u201d<ref name=\"Beating\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.irishexaminer.com/lifestyle/artsfilmtv/bilingual-folk-pop-band-seo-linn-are-guided-by-a-beating-heart-as-gaeilge-448056.html|title=Bilingual folk-pop band Seo Linn are guided by a beating heart, as Gaeilge |date=2017-04-18 |website=[[IrishExaminer.com]] |access-date=2019-06-07}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Seo Linn Performing in Vicar Street 2017.jpg|thumb|Seo Linn headlining Vicar Street in 2017]]\n\n=== ''Marcus in the Wood/Marcas sa gCoill'' (2019) ===\n\nSeo Linn released their first EP ''Marcus in the Wood/Marcas sa gCoill'' in July 2019 containing singles, ''Buy Me Time/Bain An Glas'' and ''Darkness Shines A Light/Soilsi\u00fa an Lae''.\n\n==Members==\n\n===Band members===\n*[[Stiof\u00e1n \u00d3 Fearail]] \u2013 lead vocals, guitars\n*Daith\u00ed \u00d3 Ruaidh \u2013 vocals, piano, keyboards, [[synthesisers]], [[saxophone]], guitars\n*Keith \u00d3 Briain \u2013 vocals, guitars, [[mandolin]], bass guitar, [[tin whistle]]\n*Kev Shortall \u2013 vocals, [[accordion]], percussion\n\n'''''Live musicians'''''\n*Colm Farrell \u2013 drums\n*Ben Wanders \u2013 drums \n\n'''''Former band members'''''\n*Conor Moore \u2013 drums, bodhr\u00e1n, percussion\n*Cathal \u00d3 Ruaidh \u2013 vocals, bass guitar, keyboards\n*Jenny N\u00ed Ruis\u00e9il - vocals, mandolin, tambourine, tin whistle, guitars\n\n== Discography ==\n* ''[[Solas (Seo Linn album)|Solas]]'' (2017)\n* ''Marcus in the Wood/Marcas sa gCoill'' (2019)\n\n== Awards and nominations ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Year\n!Nominated work\n!Association\n!Category\n!Result\n!{{Abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" |2018\n| rowspan=\"4\" |''Solas''\n| rowspan=\"2\" |N\u00d3S Music Awards\n|Album of the Year\n| {{won}}\n| style=\"text-align:center\" |<ref name=\"tca2010\">{{cite web|url=http://teenchoiceawards.com/pdf/TC10-Winners.pdf|title=Winners of \"Teen Choice 2010\" Announced|publisher=Teen Choice Awards|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110609194647/http://teenchoiceawards.com/pdf/TC10-Winners.pdf|archivedate=June 9, 2011|accessdate=February 4, 2014}}</ref>\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{official website}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:High Kings, The}}\n[[Category:Irish folk musical groups]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from Dublin (city)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Seo Linn\n| image            =\n| image_size       = 250\n| caption          = Seo Linn in 2019\n| background       = group_or_band\n| years_active     = 2013\u2013current\n| website          = {{url|seolinn.com/}}\n| origin           = Ireland\n| genre            = [[Irish Music]], [[Folk music|Folk Music]], [[Pop Music]], [[Celtic Music|Celtic]]\n| current_members  = [[Stiof\u00e1n \u00d3 Fearail]]<br/>Daith\u00ed \u00d3 Ruaidh<br/>Keith \u00d3 Briain<br/>Kev Shortall\n}}\n\n'''Seo Linn''' ({{IPA-ga|\u0283\u0254 l\u02b2\u026an\u0320\u02b2|}}, \"this with us\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ancroiait.wordpress.com/2013/09/18/123-learn-irish-some-nights/|title=123. Learn Irish \u2013 Some Nights|date=September 18, 2013}}</ref>) is an Irish folk/pop/rock group formed in Ireland that has been making music and performing since 2013.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/life-and-style/people/a-cure-has-been-found-for-irish-language-phobia-1.2556915|title=A cure has been found for Irish-language phobia|last=Valentine|first=Aoife|website=The Irish Times|language=en|access-date=2019-06-07}}</ref> The group consists of [[Stiof\u00e1n \u00d3 Fearail]] on vocals and guitar, Daith\u00ed \u00d3 Ruaidh on vocals, keyboard, and saxophone, Keith \u00d3 Briain on vocals, bass guitar, mandolin, and percussion, and Kevin Shortall on vocals, accordion, and percussion. They perform in both [[Irish language|Irish]] and [[English language|English]].\n\nTheir debut album, 'Solas', was released in 2017 featuring songs such as 'Ar Sc\u00e1th A Ch\u00e9ile', 'Music Makers' and their powerful rendition of the traditional Irish song, [[\u00d3r\u00f3 s\u00e9 do bheatha abhaile|\u00d3r\u00f3 'S\u00e9 Do Bheatha Abhaile]] entitled '\u00d3r\u00f3' on the album. The album won at the N\u00f3s Music Awards for '2017 Album of the Year'. The album consisted of a collection of songs that they had been writing since 2013 for vaious projects along with newly written material specifically for the album itself. Solas is the Irish word for 'light' and the image of a lightblub appears on the front of their CD symbolising a new idea and approach towards normalising the Irish language within contemporary folk-pop music.\n\nSeo Linn's second collection of original material entitled 'Marcus in the Wood/Marcas sa gCoill' is set for release in July 2019.\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Early Years (2013 - 2017) ===\n\nThe band rose to prominence after meeting in [[Col\u00e1iste Lurgan]] in the Conamara Gaeltacht of West Galway where they worked for years establishing the TG Lurgan YouTube channel. Since the release of their 2013 cover video of [[Avicii]]'s 'Wake Me Up' both the TG Lurgan channel and the newly formed Seo Linn started to make waves.\n\nBy 2016, they had played [[Croke Park]], [[3Arena|The 3Arena]], [[Aviva Stadium]], [[Bord G\u00e1is Energy Theatre|The Board G\u00e1is Energy Theatre]], and a headline show in [[Vicar Street]].<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://seolinn.com/about/|title=About|website=Seo Linn|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-05-21}}</ref> They also managed to amass 32 million views on YouTube videos in this period and international headliner gigs in [[New York City|New York]], [[Melbourne]], [[Boston]], [[London]], [[Paris]], [[Edinburgh]] and even [[Uganda]].<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n=== Debut Album ''Solas'' (2017) ===\n\nSeo Linn wrote their first ever song, 'Ar Sc\u00e1th a Ch\u00e9ile' in Uganda in 2013 while the band were there with Irish charity [[Self Help Africa]]. The song is an uplifting song that speaks of the value behind the idea the 'unity is strength'. The song contains a lyric in [[Lugandan]], the Bantu language of the Baganda people of Uganda, that says 'kwegata bwe bugumu' which literally translates to 'togetherness is strength'. This phrase mirrors the Irish language phrase from which the song was titled, 'ar sc\u00e1th a ch\u00e9ile a mhaireann na daoine' meaning 'together people prosper'.\n\nIn 2016, as part of [[RT\u00c9]]'s widely acclaimed production entitled [[RT\u00c9 Centenary]], Seo Linn were chosen to write and record the song for the finale. They were asked to produce a contemporary, energetic, bilingual song inspired by lyrics from [[Arthur O'Shaughnessy]]'s 'Ode'. The line 'we are the music makers, we are the dreamer of dreams' was used in the chorus.\n\nSeo Linn's track \"[[The Irish Roar]]\" was chosen as the official [[Football Association of Ireland]] song for [[Euro 2016]]. Recorded in [[\u00c1ras Chr\u00f3n\u00e1in]] in [[Clondalkin]], the track tells the story of Irish successes in previous competitions and pays homage to travelling Irish fans.\n\nIn 'Sonas Studios' in [[Killarney]], [[Co. Kerry]], Seo Linn along with their producer, James Darkin, locked themselves in the studio for a whole night in order to create a modern take on the Irish traditional classic '\u00d3r\u00f3 'S\u00e9 Do Bheatha Abhaile' which resulted in their final track on the album '\u00d3r\u00f3'. Seo Linn's \u00d3r\u00f3 instantly became a fan favourite has amassed over 2 million views on YouTube alone.\n\n\"Accompanying the album is an interactive workbook for irish language learners with lyrics and chords, plus text written by the band on topics as diverse as sport, recipes, and even mallachta\u00ed, or insults, all as Gaeilge.\"<ref name=\"Beating\"/>  \"It encapsulates the band\u2019s ethos: \u201cEssentially what we\u2019re trying to do with the book is to take [Gaeilge] out of the classroom setting and make it real for young people.\u201d<ref name=\"Beating\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.irishexaminer.com/lifestyle/artsfilmtv/bilingual-folk-pop-band-seo-linn-are-guided-by-a-beating-heart-as-gaeilge-448056.html|title=Bilingual folk-pop band Seo Linn are guided by a beating heart, as Gaeilge |date=2017-04-18 |website=[[IrishExaminer.com]] |access-date=2019-06-07}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Seo Linn Performing in Vicar Street 2017.jpg|thumb|Seo Linn headlining Vicar Street in 2017]]\n\n=== ''Marcus in the Wood/Marcas sa gCoill'' (2019) ===\n\nSeo Linn are set to release ''Marcus in the Wood/Marcas sa gCoill'' in July 2019 containing previously released singles, ''Buy Me Time/Bain An Glas'' and ''Darkness Shines A Light/Soilsi\u00fa an Lae''.\n\n==Members==\n\n===Band members===\n*[[Stiof\u00e1n \u00d3 Fearail]] \u2013 lead vocals, guitars\n*Daith\u00ed \u00d3 Ruaidh \u2013 vocals, piano, keyboards, [[synthesisers]], [[saxophone]], guitars\n*Keith \u00d3 Briain \u2013 vocals, guitars, [[mandolin]], bass guitar, [[tin whistle]]\n*Kev Shortall \u2013 vocals, [[accordion]], percussion\n\n'''''Live musicians'''''\n*Colm Farrell \u2013 drums\n\n'''''Former band members'''''\n*Conor Moore \u2013 drums, bodhr\u00e1n, percussion\n*Cathal \u00d3 Ruaidh \u2013 vocals, bass guitar, keyboards\n*Jenny N\u00ed Ruis\u00e9il - vocals, mandolin, tambourine, tin whistle, guitars\n\n== Discography ==\n* ''[[Solas (Seo Linn album)|Solas]]'' (2017)\n* ''Marcus in the Wood/Marcas sa gCoill'' (2019)\n\n== Awards and nominations ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Year\n!Nominated work\n!Association\n!Category\n!Result\n!{{Abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" |2018\n| rowspan=\"4\" |''Solas''\n| rowspan=\"2\" |N\u00d3S Music Awards\n|Album of the Year\n| {{won}}\n| style=\"text-align:center\" |<ref name=\"tca2010\">{{cite web|url=http://teenchoiceawards.com/pdf/TC10-Winners.pdf|title=Winners of \"Teen Choice 2010\" Announced|publisher=Teen Choice Awards|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110609194647/http://teenchoiceawards.com/pdf/TC10-Winners.pdf|archivedate=June 9, 2011|accessdate=February 4, 2014}}</ref>\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{official website}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:High Kings, The}}\n[[Category:Irish folk musical groups]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from Dublin (city)]]\n", "name_user": "212.129.81.122", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Updated material)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Seo_Linn"}
{"title_page": "Conrad Veidt", "text_new": "{{short description|German actor}}\n{{EngvarB|date=October 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Conrad Veidt\n| image         = Conrad Veidt 1941.jpg\n| imagesize     = \n| caption       = Conrad Veidt in 1941\n| birth_name     = Hans Walter Conrad Veidt\n| birth_date     = {{birth date|df=yes|1893|1|22}}\n| birth_place    = [[Berlin]], [[German Empire]]\n| death_date     = {{death date and age|df=yes|1943|4|3|1893|1|22}}\n| death_place    = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], U.S.\n| othername     = \n| occupation    = Actor\n| years_active   = 1917\u20131943\n| spouse        = {{marriage|[[Gussy Holl]] |1918|1922|end=divorced}}<br />{{marriage|Felicitas Radke |1923|1932|end=divorced}}<br />{{marriage|Ilona Prager |1933}}\n| children      = 1\n| homepage      = \n}}\n\n'''Hans Walter Conrad Veidt''' ({{IPAc-en|f|a\u026a|t}}; 22 January 1893 \u2013 3 April 1943) was a [[Germany|German]] actor best remembered for his roles in films such as ''[[Different from the Others]]'' (1919), ''[[The Cabinet of Dr. Caligari]]'' (1920), and ''[[The Man Who Laughs (1928 film)|The Man who Laughs]]'' (1928). After a successful career in German silent films, where he was one of the best-paid stars of [[UFA GmbH|UFA]], he and his new Jewish wife Ilona Prager were forced to leave Germany in 1933 after the [[Nazism|Nazis]] came to power. The couple settled in Britain, where he took British citizenship in 1939. He appeared in many British films, including ''[[The Thief of Bagdad (1940 film)|The Thief of Bagdad]]'' (1940), before emigrating to the United States around 1941, which led to him being cast as Major Strasser in ''[[Casablanca (film)|Casablanca]]'' (1942).\n\n==Early life==\nVeidt was born in a [[bourgeois]] district of [[Berlin]], in what was then the German Empire, to Amalie Marie (n\u00e9e Gohtz) and Phillip Heinrich Veidt.<ref name=bptt>{{cite book|last=Allen|first=Jarry|title=Conrad Veidt: from Caligari to Casablanca|page=5|publisher=boxwood|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aMJZAAAAMAAJ&q=%22Phillip+Heinrich+Veidt%22&dq=%22Phillip+Heinrich+Veidt%22&hl=en|isbn=978-0940168046}}</ref> (Some biographies wrongly state that he was born in [[Potsdam]], probably on the basis of an early claim on his part.) His family was [[Lutheran]].<ref name=bptt/>\n\nIn 1914, Veidt met actress [[Lucie Mannheim]], with whom he began a relationship. Later in the year Veidt was [[conscription|conscripted]] into the [[German Army]] during [[World War I]].  In 1915, he was sent to the [[Eastern Front (World War I)|Eastern Front]] as a non-commissioned officer and took part in the [[Great Retreat (Russian)|Battle of Warsaw]]. He contracted [[jaundice]] and [[pneumonia]], and had to be evacuated to a hospital on the [[Baltic Sea]]. While recuperating, he received a letter from Mannheim telling him that she had found work at a theatre in [[Liep\u0101ja|Libau]]. Intrigued, Veidt applied for the theatre as well. As his condition had not improved, the army allowed him to join the theatre so that he could entertain the troops. While performing at the theatre, he ended his relationship with Mannheim. In late 1916, he was re-examined by the Army and deemed unfit for service; he was given a full discharge in January 1917. Veidt returned to Berlin to pursue his acting career.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thethunderchild.com/ConradVeidt/page94.html|title=Conrad Veidt: The Cinema's Master|publisher=The Conrad Veidt Society}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://eric.b.olsen.tripod.com/veidt.html|title=Conrad Veidt|publisher=A History of Horror|access-date=3 April 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110309215410/http://eric.b.olsen.tripod.com/veidt.html|archive-date=9 March 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.monsterzine.com/200010/conradveidt1.html|title=Conrad Veidt: Cinema\u2019s Dark Prince, 1893\u20131943|publisher=Monster Zine|date=October\u2013December 2000|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050207182606/http://monsterzine.com/200010/conradveidt1.html|archivedate=7 February 2005}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n[[File:Conrad Veidt by Becker & Maass.jpg|thumb|Veidt, c. 1920]]\nFrom 1916 until his death, Veidt appeared in more than 100 films. One of his earliest performances was as the murderous somnambulist Cesare in director [[Robert Wiene]]'s ''[[The Cabinet of Dr. Caligari]]'' (1920), a classic of [[German Expressionism#Cinema and architecture|German Expressionist]] cinema, with [[Werner Krauss]] and [[Lil Dagover]]. His starring role in ''[[The Man Who Laughs (1928 film)|The Man Who Laughs]]'' (1928), as a disfigured circus performer whose face is cut into a permanent grin, provided the (visual) inspiration for the [[Batman]] villain [[Joker (comics)|the Joker]]. Veidt starred in other silent horror films such as ''[[The Hands of Orlac (1924 film)|The Hands of Orlac]]'' (1924), also directed by Robert Wiene, ''[[The Student of Prague (1926 film)|The Student of Prague]]'' (1926) and ''[[Waxworks (film)|Waxworks]]'' (1924), in which he played [[Ivan the Terrible]].\n[[File:Konrad Fajt.png|thumb|left|Painting of Conrad Veidt by [[Milena Pavlovi\u0107-Barili]].|alt=Konrad Fajt.png]]\nVeidt also appeared in [[Magnus Hirschfeld]]'s film ''Anders als die Andern'' (''[[Different from the Others]]'', 1919), one of the earliest films to sympathetically portray homosexuality, although the characters in it do not end up happily.<ref name=\"badass\">{{cite web|url=http://badassdigest.com/2013/07/09/meet-conrad-veidt-badass/|title=Meet Conrad Veidt, Badass |publisher=Badass Digest|date=9 July 2013}}</ref> He had a leading role in Germany's first talking picture, ''Das Land ohne Frauen'' (''[[Land Without Women]]'', 1929).#calebcares\n\nHe moved to Hollywood in the late 1920s and made a few films there, but the advent of talking pictures and his difficulty with speaking English led him to return to Germany.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">[[Turner Classic Movies]] ''Conrad Veidt''</ref> During this period, he lent his expertise to tutoring aspiring performers, one of whom was the later American character actress Lisa Golm.\n\n==Emigration==\nVeidt fervently opposed the [[Nazism|Nazi]] regime and later donated a major portion of his personal fortune to Britain to assist in the war effort. Soon after the [[Nazi Party]] took power in Germany, by March 1933, [[Joseph Goebbels]] was purging the film industry of anti-Nazi sympathizers and Jews, and so in 1933, a week after Veidt's marriage to Ilona Prager, a Jewish woman, the couple emigrated to Britain before any action could be taken against either of them.\n\nGoebbels had imposed a \"racial questionnaire\" in which everyone employed in the German film industry had to declare their \"race\" to continue to work. When Veidt was filling in the questionnaire, he answered the question about what his ''Rasse'' (race) was by writing that he was a ''Jude'' (Jew).<ref name=\"Hull, David Stewart page 90\">Hull, David Stewart ''Film in the Third Reich'', New York: Simon & Schuster, 1973 page 90.</ref> Veidt was not Jewish, but his wife was Jewish, and Veidt would not renounce the woman he loved.<ref name=\"Hull, David Stewart page 90\"/> Additionally, Veidt, who was opposed to [[antisemitism]], wanted to show solidarity with the German Jewish community, who were in the process of being stripped of their rights as German citizens in the spring of 1933. As one of Germany's most prominent actors, Veidt had been informed that if he was prepared to divorce his wife and declare his support for the new regime, he could continue to act in Germany. Several other leading actors who had been opposed to the Nazis before 1933 switched allegiances. In answering the questionnaire by stating he was a Jew, Veidt rendered himself unemployable in Germany, but stated this sacrifice was worth it as there was nothing in the world that would compel him to break with his wife.<ref name=\"Hull, David Stewart page 90\"/> Upon hearing about what Veidt had done, Goebbels remarked that he would never act in Germany again.\n\n[[File:SpyInBlack-Veidt.jpg|thumbnail|Conrad Veidt in ''[[The Spy in Black]]'' (1939)]]\nAfter arriving in Britain, Veidt perfected his English and starred in the title roles of the original anti-Nazi versions of ''[[The Wandering Jew (1933 film)|The Wandering Jew]]'' (1933) and ''[[Jew S\u00fcss (1934 film)|Jew S\u00fcss]]'' (1934), the latter film was directed by the exiled German-born director [[Lothar Mendes]] and produced by [[Michael Balcon]] for [[Gaumont-British]]. He naturalised as a [[British subject]] on 25 February 1939.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=34605 |date=7 March 1939 |page=1546}}</ref> By this point multi-lingual, Veidt made films in both French with expatriate French directors and in English, including three of his best-known roles for British director [[Michael Powell]] in ''[[The Spy in Black]]'' (1939), ''[[Contraband (1940 film)|Contraband]]'' (1940) and ''[[The Thief of Bagdad (1940 film)|The Thief of Bagdad]]'' (1940).\n\n===Later career in the US===\nBy 1941, he and Ilona had settled in Hollywood to assist in the British effort in making American films that might persuade the then-neutral and still [[isolationist]] US to join the war against the Nazis, who had conquered all of continental Europe and were [[battle of Britain|bombing the United Kingdom]] at the time. Before leaving the United Kingdom, Veidt gave his life savings to the British government to help finance the war effort.<ref name=\"badass\"/> Realizing that Hollywood would most likely typecast him in Nazi roles, he had his contract mandate that they must always be villains.<ref name=\"badass\"/>\n\nHe starred in a few films, such as [[George Cukor]]'s ''[[A Woman's Face]]'' (1941) where he received billing under [[Joan Crawford]]'s and ''[[Nazi Agent]]'' (1942), in which he had a dual role as both an aristocratic German Nazi spy and as the man's twin brother, an anti-Nazi American. His best-known Hollywood role was as the sinister Major Heinrich Strasser in ''[[Casablanca (film)|Casablanca]]'' (1942), a film which began pre-production before the United States entered [[World War II]].\n\n==Personal life==\nConrad Veidt married three times: he first married [[Gussy Holl]], a [[cabaret]] entertainer, on 18 June 1918.<ref>https://books.google.com/books?id=aMJZAAAAMAAJ&q=gussy+holl&dq=gussy+holl&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiw3pDEwtfoAhVNQq0KHTzYCIoQ6AEISTAJ</ref> They divorced four years later. Gussy later married German actor [[Emil Jannings]]. Some sources say Veidt had a daughter named Ruth-Maria with Holl.<ref>https://books.google.com/books?id=QfUKAQAAMAAJ&q=ruth+maria+jannings&dq=ruth+maria+jannings&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjWxfHzjuHoAhVMF6wKHZlvA7oQ6AEIKzAF</ref>\n\nVeidt's second wife Felicitas Radke was from an aristocratic German family; they married in 1923. Their daughter, Vera Viola Maria, called Viola, was born on 10 August 1925. He last married Ilona Prager, a Hungarian Jew called Lily, in 1933; they remained together until his death.{{citation needed|date=October 2017}}<!-- WP:RS needed; removed link to WP:SPS (Twitter, FB, WP)-->\n\n==Death==\nConrad Veidt died on 3 April 1943 of a massive heart attack while playing golf at the [[Riviera Country Club]] in Los Angeles with singer [[Arthur Fields]] and his personal physician, Dr. Bergman, who pronounced him dead on the scene.<ref name=\"badass\"/><ref>\"Conrad Veidt Obituary,\" ''Los Angeles Times'', 1943</ref> Veidt was 50 years old. In 1998, his ashes were placed in a niche of the columbarium at the [[Golders Green Crematorium]] in north London.<ref>{{cite web|title=Newspaper reports of reinterrment|url=http://thethunderchild.com/ActorSites/ConradVeidt/Life/Guardian.html#Golders|website=Conrad Veidt Society|accessdate=23 November 2017}}</ref><ref>[https://books.google.ca/books?id=hxWBCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA25&dq=conrad+veidt+Golders+Green+Crematorium&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiD9IWes7bfAhWLsVQKHYCNBhkQ6AEIKjAA#v=onepage&q=conrad%20veidt%20Golders%20Green%20Crematorium&f=false ''Conrad Veidt on Screen'']</ref>\n\n==Complete filmography==\t\t\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width=\"100%\"\n! Year !! Title !! Role !! Notes\n|-\n| 1917 || ''[[When the Dead Speak]]'' || Richard von Worth ||\n|-\n| 1917 || ''[[Fear (1917 film)|Fear]]'' || Indian Priest ||\n|-\n| 1917 || ''[[The Sea Battle]]'' || ||\n|-\n| 1917 || ''[[The Spy (1917 German film)|The Spy]]'' || Steinau ||\n|-\n| 1918 || ''[[The Mystery of Bangalore]]'' || Dinja ||\n|-\n| 1918 || ''[[The Serenyi]]'' || ||\n|-\n| 1918 || ''[[The Path of Death]]'' || Rolf ||\n|-\n| 1918 || ''[[The Mexican (1918 film)|The Mexican]]'' || ||\n|-\n| 1918 || ''[[The House of Three Girls (1918 film)|The House of Three Girls]]'' || Baron Schober ||\n|-\n| 1918 || ''[[Diary of a Lost Woman]]'' || Dr. Julius ||\n|-\n| 1918 || ''[[Jettchen Gebert's Story]]'' || Doctor Friedrich K\u00f6stling ||\n|-\n| 1918 || ''[[Colomba (film)|Colomba]]'' || Henrik van Rhyn ||\n|-\n| 1918 || ''[[Let There Be Light (1917 film)|Let There Be Light]]'' || Herr Kramer ||\n|-\n| 1918 || ''[[The Story of Dida Ibsen]]'' || Erik Norrensen ||\n|-\n| 1918 || ''[[Henriette Jacoby]]'' || Doctor Friedrich K\u00f6stling ||\n|-\n| 1918 || ''[[Victim of Society]]'' || Prosecutor Chrysander ||\n|-\n| 1918 || ''[[Not of the Woman Born]]'' || [[Satan]] ||\n|-\n| 1919 || ''[[Opium (1919 film)|Opium]]'' || Dr. Richard Armstrong Jr. ||\n|-\n| 1919 || ''[[Nocturne of Love (1919 film)|Nocturne of Love]]'' || [[Frederic Chopin]] ||\n|-\n| 1919 || ''[[The Japanese Woman]]'' || The Secretary ||\n|-\n| 1919 || ''[[Prostitution (1919 film)|Prostitution]]'' || Alfred Werner ||\n|-\n| 1919 || ''[[Around the World in Eighty Days (1919 film)|Around the World in Eighty Days]]'' || [[Phineas Fogg]] ||\n|-\n| 1919 || ''[[Peer Gynt (1919 film)|Peer Gynt]]'' (2 parts) || Ein fremder Passagier ||\n|-\n| 1919 || ''[[Different from the Others]]'' || Paul K\u00f6