8]]\n| {{dts|2002|November|1|format=mdy}}\n| align=center| 2\n| align=center| 1:24\n| [[Reno, Nevada]], United States\n| \n|-\n| {{no2}}Loss\n| align=center| 3\u20131\n| [[Dan Bobish]]\n| Submission (punches)\n| [[2002 in King of the Cage#KOTC 13 - Revolution|KOTC 13]]\n| {{dts|2002|May|17|format=mdy}}\n| align=center| 1\n| align=center| 3:25\n| [[Reno, Nevada]], United States\n| <small>For [[List of KOTC champions#Super Heavyweight Championship|KOTC Super Heavyweight Championship]].</small>\n|-\n| {{yes2}}Win\n| align=center| 3\u20130\n| Nate Russak\n| Submission (punches)\n| Gladiator Challenge 9\n| {{dts|2002|February|10|format=mdy}}\n| align=center| 1\n| align=center| 2:39\n| [[San Jacinto, California]], United States\n| \n|-\n| {{yes2}}Win\n| align=center| 2\u20130\n| Kauai Kupihea\n| KO (punches)\n| Night of the Knockout 2\n| {{dts|2001|June|9|format=mdy}}\n| align=center| 2\n| align=center| N/A\n| [[Boise, Idaho]], United States\n| \n|-\n| {{yes2}}Win\n| align=center| 1\u20130\n| Andrew Boyle\n| TKO (punches)\n| Night of the Knockout 1\n| {{dts|2001|March|10|format=mdy}}\n| align=center| 1\n| align=center| 1:30\n| [[Boise, Idaho]], United States\n| \n{{end}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of male mixed martial artists]]\n* [[List of current WSOF fighters]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Sherdog}}\n* {{UFC|Mike-Kyle}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kyle, Mike}}\n[[Category:American male mixed martial artists]]\n[[Category:Mixed martial artists from Idaho]]\n[[Category:Light heavyweight mixed martial artists]]\n[[Category:Heavyweight mixed martial artists]]\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:African-American mixed martial artists]]\n[[Category:Ultimate Fighting Championship male fighters]]\n[[Category:African-American boxers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{short description|American mixed martial arts fighter}}\n{{Infobox martial artist\n| name            = Mike Kyle\n| other_names     = MAK\n| image           = Mike Kyle.jpg\n| image_size      = 200px\n| alt             =\n| caption         = Mike Kyle in 2009, at the weigh-in before the [[Strikeforce: Carano vs. Cyborg]] event\n| birth_name      = Michael Kyle\n| birth_date      = {{birth date and age|1980|03|31}}\n| birth_place     = [[Boise, Idaho]], United States\n| death_date      =\n| death_place     =\n| death_cause     =\n| residence       = [[San Jose, California]], United States\n| nationality     = American\n| height          = {{height|ft=6|in=3}}\n| weight_lb       = 241.4\n| weight_class    = [[Super Heavyweight (MMA)|Super Heavyweight]]<br>[[Heavyweight (MMA)|Heavyweight]]<br>[[Light Heavyweight (MMA)|Light Heavyweight]]\n| reach_in        = 77.0\n| style           =\n| stance          = Orthodox\n| fighting_out_of = [[San Jose, California]], United States\n| team            = [[American Kickboxing Academy]]\n| rank            =\n| years_active    = 2001\u2013''present''\n| mma_kowin       = 17\n| mma_subwin      = 2\n| mma_decwin      = 4\n| mma_koloss      = 8\n| mma_subloss     = 6\n| mma_decloss     = 4\n| mma_dqloss      = 1\n| mma_draw        = 1\n| mma_nc          = 2\n| sherdog         = 3619\n| box_win         = 1\n| box_kowin       = 1\n| box_loss        = 3\n| box_koloss      =\n| box_draw        =\n| box_nc          =\n| footnotes       =\n| updated         =\n}}\n\n'''Mike Kyle''' (born March 31, 1980) is an American professional [[mixed martial arts|mixed martial artist]] and [[boxing|boxer]] currently competing in the [[Heavyweight (MMA)|Heavyweight]] division. A professional competitor since 2001, Kyle has competed for the [[Ultimate Fighting Championship|UFC]], the [[World Extreme Cagefighting|WEC]], [[Strikeforce (mixed martial arts)|Strikeforce]], the [[World Series of Fighting]], [[Absolute Championship Berkut]], [[Pancrase]], [[King of the Cage]], and is the former [[List of KOTC champions#Light Heavyweight Championship|King of the Cage Light Heavyweight Champion]].\n\n==Background==\nKyle is from [[Boise, Idaho]]. He attended [[Nampa High School]] and was friends with the late [[Justin Eilers]], who Kyle would actually end up fighting in his second fight for the UFC. Eilers and a friend who were both two grades ahead of Kyle, taught him [[Brazilian jiu-jitsu]] techniques when he was a sophomore in high school. Kyle was also a talented football player, playing fullback for [[Butte College]] in [[Oroville, California]] and [[Eastern Oregon University]]. During his early mixed martial arts career he split time between fighting and playing football. He was invited to a spring camp for the [[San Francisco 49ers]], but ultimately decided to focus on [[mixed martial arts]].<ref name=\"411mania.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.411mania.com/MMA/columns/180490/411-Fighter-Profile-04.04.11:-Mike-Kyle.htm |title=411MANIA  |work=411 Fighter Profile 04.04.11: Mike Kyle |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131019162412/http://www.411mania.com/MMA/columns/180490/411-Fighter-Profile-04.04.11%3A-Mike-Kyle.htm |archivedate=October 19, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Mixed martial arts career==\n===Early career===\nKyle held an undefeated amateur record of 3\u20130 before turning professional. Kyle made his professional debut on March 10, 2001, when he was 18 years old and won by [[Knockout|TKO]] only 90 seconds into the fight. He then won his next two fights, also by punches before debuting in the [[King of the Cage]] promotion. Kyle made his King of the Cage debut in a fight for the [[List of KOTC champions|King of the Cage Super Heavyweight Championship]] against then [[List of KOTC champions|King of the Cage Super Heavyweight Champion]] [[Dan Bobish]]. Kyle, who then weighed 275 lbs. was outweighed by Bobish, who was 55 lbs. bigger than Kyle. Despite rocking Bobish early in the fight and almost pulling off the upset, Kyle was handed his first career loss after he submitted due to punches. In his next [[King of the Cage|KOTC]] bout, Kyle made his [[Heavyweight (MMA)|Heavyweight]] debut against future [[List of KOTC champions|King of the Cage Heavyweight Champion]] [[Paul Buentello]]. Kyle lost after he was knocked out from punches. After losing to Buentello, the San Jose-based [[American Kickboxing Academy]] invited Kyle to train. He accepted and has been training with AKA ever since.<ref name=\"411mania.com\"/>\n\nIn his next fight, Kyle made his debut in the [[World Extreme Cagefighting|WEC]], and snapped his two-fight losing streak with a knockout win. The 4\u20132 Kyle then fought in the IFC and again won by strikes as his opponent tapped out due to punches. Kyle then also won his next two fights, which included another win under the WEC banner.<ref name=\"411mania.com\"/>\n\n===Ultimate Fighting Championship===\nKyle made his [[Ultimate Fighting Championship|UFC]] debut against [[Wes Sims (fighter)|Wes Sims]] winning via KO at 4:59 of round one. Sims took the fight a days notice notice after Kyle's original opponent filled into the main event after [[Tim Sylvia]] failed a drug test. Kyle dominated the entire first round and knocked Sims out at 4:59. Sims protested after the fight that Kyle had bitten him on the chest.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onzuka.com/news_2004April3.html |title=Hawaii Martial Arts News & Rumors \u2013 Dedicated to Hawaii-Specific Martial Arts News & Rumors |publisher=Onzuka.com |accessdate=16 July 2015}}</ref> During the post-fight interview, a bite mark could clearly be seen on Sims' left [[pectoralis major muscle|pectoral muscle]]. This marks the first time a bite has ever happened in a UFC fight since its inception at [[UFC 1]] in 1993, when [[Gerard Gordeau]] bit [[Royce Gracie]] in the championship match. Kyle still denies any wrongdoing.\n\nKyle then fought the late [[Justin Eilers]] in a [[Heavyweight (MMA)|Heavyweight]] bout. This was a significant match up as Eilers was a friend of Kyle's who had actually introduced Kyle to the sport of mixed martial arts. Kyle lost the fight when he was knocked out from a punch 74 seconds into the first round.<ref name=\"411mania.com\"/>\n\nHe then fought former [[List of WEC champions#Heavyweight Championship|WEC Heavyweight Champion]] [[James Irvin (fighter)|James Irvin]] at [[UFC 51]] winning via knockout in the first round. Despite this relatively notable win in the UFC, Kyle requested his release in from the UFC to compete in [[Japan]].\n\n===Post-UFC===\nKyle then left the UFC and had planned to fight in the [[PRIDE Fighting Championships]] in Japan. However, the plan fell through and in his next bout he fought in Japan's [[Pancrase]] where he defeated Japanese legend [[Tsuyoshi Kohsaka]]. Kyle won the fight via (technical) decision in round three after ringside doctors ruled Kohsaka unable to continue. Kyle had cut down from 245 lbs. to 230 lbs. for the fight. He then fought against [[Devin Cole]] at [[WEC 18|WEC 18: Unfinished Business]], and lost by TKO. This was Kyle's first defeat in the [[World Extreme Cagefighting|WEC]].<ref name=\"411mania.com\"/>\n\n===Strikeforce===\nHe then signed with [[Strikeforce (mixed martial arts)|Strikeforce]], making his debut against [[Krzysztof Soszynski]] in a [[Heavyweight (MMA)|Heavyweight]] bout at [[List of Strikeforce events|Strikeforce: Shamrock vs. Gracie]]. The fight was declared a technical draw after Soszynski was accidentally poked in the eye by Kyle. Kyle then fought [[Brian Olsen]] for the [[List of WEC champions#Heavyweight Championship|WEC Heavyweight Championship]] and was disqualified after he hit Olsen with illegal strikes, for which he was placed on the national suspension list, and given an 18-month ban. After throwing Olsen over his shoulder, Kyle hit Olsen, who was on his knees and therefore a grounded opponent, with a soccer kick and then repeatedly hit him with strikes, continuing to hit Olsen even after fight referee Josh Rosenthal had physically tried to separate them, and did not stop until referee Herb Dean ran into the cage to assist Rosenthal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mmafanatics.blogspot.com/2006/05/mike-kyle-on-national-suspension-list.html|title=Mike Kyle on national suspension list for kicking a downed fighter|accessdate=August 14, 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe 10\u20135\u20131 Kyle then fought at [[List of Strikeforce events|Strikeforce: Shamrock vs. Le]] against former All-American [[wrestling|wrestler]] Wayne Cole in a [[Heavyweight (MMA)|Heavyweight]] bout and lost after he was submitted from an [[armbar]]. Kyle then returned to the IFC and won his bout via knockout, and followed this up with another win, this time via unanimous decision, his first career decision win. Kyle then returned to Strikeforce to fight [[Rafael Cavalcante]] in a [[Light Heavyweight (MMA)|Light Heavyweight]] bout at [[List of Strikeforce events|Strikeforce: Lawler vs. Shields]]. Kyle picked up one of the biggest victories of his career, winning by knockout against the future [[List of Strikeforce champions|Strikeforce Light Heavyweight Champion]]. This was also significant because it was Calvacante's first decisive loss, as his only other defeat was by disqualification against [[Marcio Cruz]].<ref name=\"411mania.com\"/>\n\nAfter his huge win over Calvacante, Kyle fought against [[Fabr\u00edcio Werdum]] in a [[Heavyweight (MMA)|Heavyweight]] bout at [[List of Strikeforce events|Strikeforce: Carano vs. Cyborg]] in [[San Jose, California]]. He lost the bout via [[guillotine choke]] submission.<ref name=\"411mania.com\"/>\n\nHe then fought Jeremy Freitag at Xtreme MMA Australia 1 winning via TKO due to knees in the third round.\n\n===King of the Cage===\nKyle next signed with [[King of the Cage]] and fought against [[Travis Wiuff]] in a [[Heavyweight (MMA)|Heavyweight]] bout, initially winning by TKO (doctor stoppage) in the second round. However, it was changed to a no contest decision after it was determined Kyle hit Wiuff after the bell.\n\nIn his second fight with [[King of the Cage]] Kyle fought [[Jon Murphy (fighter)|Jon Murphy]] and won via TKO at 4:53 of round two. He then fought Tony Lopez for the [[King of the Cage#Current champions|King of the Cage Light Heavyweight Championship]] and won via split decision after a five-round battle, becoming the [[List of KOTC champions|King of the Cage Light Heavyweight Champion]].\n\n===Return to Strikeforce===\nKyle fought against Abongo Humphrey at [[List of Strikeforce events|Strikeforce Challengers: del Rosario vs. Mahe]]. Kyle won via submission in the second round.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lowkick.com/UFC/ShoMMA-9-Rosario-vs-Mahe-Quick-Results-LowPick-winneers-announced-9203|title=ShoMMA 9: Rosario vs Mahe Results|accessdate=August 14, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100728013059/http://www.lowkick.com/UFC/ShoMMA-9-Rosario-vs-Mahe-Quick-Results-LowPick-winneers-announced-9203|archive-date=July 28, 2010|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nKyle fought against Steve Oliver at Xtreme MMA Australia 3 Kyle won via TKO due to punches in round one, winning the XMMA Light Heavyweight Championship.\n\nKyle stepped in on late notice to fight [[Ant\u00f4nio Silva (fighter)|Ant\u00f4nio \"Bigfoot\" Silva]] at [[Strikeforce: Henderson vs. Babalu II]] on December 4 in [[St. Louis, Missouri]] in a Heavyweight bout.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mmaweekly.com/mike-kyle-tapped-to-face-antonio-silva-for-strikeforce|title=Mike Kyle Tapped to Face Antonio Silva for Strikeforce|work=MMA Weekly|date=November 29, 2010}}</ref> Kyle knocked Silva down with a powerful right hand and delivered many shots on the ground but was unable to finish. Silva defeated Kyle via second-round TKO. Kyle later revealed that he broke his hand during the fight.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mmajunkie.com/news/21631/despite-loss-mike-kyle-still-in-thick-of-strikeforce-light-heavyweight-title-picture.mma |title=Despite loss, Mike Kyle still in thick of Strikeforce light-heavyweight title picture |accessdate=December 5, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101208031234/http://mmajunkie.com/news/21631/despite-loss-mike-kyle-still-in-thick-of-strikeforce-light-heavyweight-title-picture.mma |archivedate=December 8, 2010 }}</ref>\n\nKyle was set to face [[Gegard Mousasi]] at [[Strikeforce: Diaz vs. Daley]], but had to withdraw due to a broken hand. Former [[Ultimate Fighting Championship|UFC]] veteran [[Keith Jardine]] stepped in on short notice as his replacement.\n\nKyle was again scheduled to fight Mousasi at [[Strikeforce World Grand Prix: Barnett vs. Kharitonov]] but Mousasi withdrew for unknown reasons and was replaced by [[Strikeforce (mixed martial arts)|Strikeforce]] newcomer [[Marcos Rog\u00e9rio de Lima]]. Kyle won by unanimous decision, picking apart the younger fighter with [[boxing]] techniques.\n\nKyle was expected to face [[Gegard Mousasi]] at [[Strikeforce: Tate vs. Rousey]], but withdrew from the fight due to injury. He next faced [[Rafael Cavalcante]] in a rematch at [[Strikeforce 40]] in what would be a title eliminator match for the vacant [[List of Strikeforce champions#Light Heavyweight Championship|Strikeforce Light Heavyweight Championship]]. Kyle lost the fight via [[guillotine choke]] in the first round.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mmamania.com/2012/5/19/3031689/strikeforce-barnett-vs-cormier-results-rafael-cavalcante-submits-mike-kyle|title=Strikeforce 'Barnett vs Cormier' results: Rafael Cavalcante submits Mike Kyle in 33 seconds|author=Geno Mrosko|work=MMAmania.com}}</ref> After the fight, Cavalcante tested positive for a banned substance and, as a result, the CSAC declared the fight a \"no contest\".\n\nKyle finally faced Mousasi at [[Strikeforce: Marquardt vs. Saffiedine]] on January 12, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.strikeforce.com/event/SF6|title=STRIKEFORCE\u00ae MARQUARDT VS. SAFFIEDINE|publisher=strikeforce.com|date=November 30, 2012}}</ref> He lost via submission in the first round. Kyle said that he would retire following the loss.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mmamania.com/2013/1/13/3871444/strikeforce-results-mike-kyle-to-retire-from-mma-following-defeat-to|title=Strikeforce results: Mike Kyle to retire from MMA following defeat to Gegard Mousasi|publisher=mmamania.com|date=January 13, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Independent Promotions===\nHe has since stated that he will not retire and he was scheduled to fight veteran [[Valentijn Overeem]] in May but Overeem was forced out due to injury.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mmaweekly.com/valentijn-overeem-injured-travis-wiuff-faces-mike-kyle-in-new-cfa-11-main-event|title=Valentijn Overeem injured Travis Wiuff Faces Mike Kyle in New CFA 11 Main Event|work=MMA Weekly|date=May 11, 2013}}</ref>\n\nKyle then had a rematch with [[Travis Wiuff]] and won via knockout only 21 seconds into the fight. Kyle landed a lead counter-left hook that rocked the back of Wiuff's head who seemed to be unconscious, Kyle then landed a hammerfist before telling the referee that Wiuff was \"out\" but the fight had not been called until Kyle landed another punch to the downed Wiuff. Kyle was visibly upset after the fight with the referee, feeling that the stoppage was late.<ref name=\"411mania.com\"/>\n\nKyle was expected to face Maxim Grishin at Fight Nights: Battle of Moscow 17 on September 30, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sherdog.com/events/Fight-Nights-Battle-of-Moscow-17-40355|title=Fight Nights: Battle of Moscow 17|publisher=sherdog.com}}</ref> However, Kyle pulled out of the bout due to injury, he was replaced with [[Trevor Prangley]].\n\nKyle faced Evgeny Erokhin on December 20, 2014, at FEFoMP: Russia's MMA Supercup.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sherdog.com/events/FEFoMP-Russias-MMA-Supercup-42411|title=FEFoMP \u2013 Russia's MMA Supercup|publisher=Sherdog.com}}</ref> He lost the fight via KO in the second round.\n\n===World Series of Fighting===\nKyle was to face former UFC veteran [[Anthony Johnson (fighter)|Anthony Johnson]] on September 14, 2013, at [[World Series of Fighting#World Series of Fighting 5|WSOF 5]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mmacore.com/videos/interviews/Anthony_Rumble_Johnson_talks_WSOF_5_fight_against_Mike_Kyle/10054069|title=Anthony Johnson talks about fighting Mike Kyle at WSOF 5|publisher=mmacore.com|date=June 17, 2013}}{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> However, Johnson was forced out of the bout due to injury and Kyle faced former [[UFC Heavyweight Championship|UFC Heavyweight Champion]] [[Andrei Arlovski]] at the event.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sherdog.com/news/news/Andrei-Arlovski-Replaces-Injured-Anthony-Johnson-Faces-Mike-Kyle-at-WSOF-5-54785|title=Andrei Arlovski Replaces Injured Anthony Johnson, Faces Mike Kyle at WSOF 5|publisher=sherdog.com|date=August 9, 2013}}</ref> Although he knocked Arlovski down with right hands in the first and third round, he lost the fight via unanimous decision.\n\nMike Kyle vs. Anthony Johnson was scheduled for December 7, 2013, in [[Vancouver]], British Columbia, Canada but was later canceled because Kyle was forced off the fight because of a broken toe.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mmajunkie.com/2013/11/wsof-7-headliner-off-after-mike-kyle-sustains-toe-injury/ |title=World Series of Fighting Canada Launches With December 7 Event in Vancouver|publisher=TopMMANews.com|date=October 2, 2013}}</ref>\n\nKyle eventually faced [[Anthony Johnson (fighter)|Anthony Johnson]] at [[World Series of Fighting 8: Gaethje vs. Patishnock|WSOF 8]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mmajunkie.com/2013/12/wsof-8-slated-for-jan-18-with-gaethje-cavalcante-title-fight-johnson-kyle-bollinger-nam/|title=WSOF 8 slated for Jan. 18 with Gaethje-Cavalcante title fight, Johnson-Kyle, Bollinger-Nam|publisher=mmajunkie.com|author=Staff|accessdate=3 December 2013|date=December 3, 2013}}</ref> Kyle lost via KO in the first round.\n\n===Absolute Championship Berkut===\nKyle faced Denis Goltsov on March 26, 2016, at [[2016 in Absolute Championship Berkut#ACB 32|ACB 32]]. He lost the fight via submission in the first round.\n\nKyle faced [[Dan Charles]] on January 13, 2017, at ACB 51.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://acbmma.com/en/tournamentnext/acb-51-3108_62 |title=Archived copy |access-date=January 14, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161227054714/http://acbmma.com/en/tournamentnext/acb-51-3108_62 |archive-date=December 27, 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He won the fight via TKO in the first round.\n\nA rematch with Evgeny Erokhin was expected to take place on July 23, 2017, at [[2017 in Absolute Championship Berkut#ACB 65|ACB 65]].<ref>[https://acbmma.com/en/tournamentnext/acb-65-ontario-california-awyEQUV2_76 ]{{dead link|date=September 2019}}</ref> However, the bout did not go ahead as planned.\n\n==Professional boxing==\nKyle made his professional boxing debut on January 17, 2003, as a [[heavyweight]], losing via unanimous decision.\n\nKyle returned to the boxing ring in 2016, winning via knockout for his first professional win. Kyle would go 0-2-1 before ending the year, however, most recently losing a unanimous decision to undefeated fighter Darmani Rock.\n\nKyle is next scheduled to face 3-0 Roberto Salas on March 23, 2019.\n\n==Personal life==\nKyle is married and has one daughter with his current wife, as well as two sons from a previous marriage.<ref>[http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/sports/despite-bad-breaks-and-broken-hands-mike-kyle-continues-hunt-for-mma-title-152096845.html ]{{dead link|date=July 2015}}</ref> He is of partial Irish descent.\n\n==Championships and accomplishments==\n*'''[[King of the Cage]]'''\n**[[List of KOTC champions#Light Heavyweight Championship|KOTC Light Heavyweight Championship]] (One time)\n*'''Xtreme MMA Australia'''\n**XMMA Light Heavyweight Championship (One time)\n\n==Mixed martial arts record==\n{{MMArecordbox\n| draws= 1\n| nc= 2\n| ko-wins= 17\n| ko-losses= 8\n| sub-wins= 2\n| sub-losses= 6\n| dec-wins= 4\n| dec-losses= 4\n| dq-wins= \n| dq-losses= 1\n| other-wins= \